Typically the torreznos are served with some pan fried homefries on the side and a couple of fried peppers as well.

There are basically 2 types of Spanish "tapas" dishes; racciones (like the torreznos, rabas, croquettas, bravas, cooked chorizo) which is served in a big portion on one plate that people can pick and choose from, usually each has a big chunk of fresh baguette bread to eat them with.

The other is what you are actually given as tapas/pintxos (picrel) in bars, which is just tiny sandwiches or single slices of bread filled or topped with some combination of serrano ham, anchovies, grilled peppers, tomato spread, shredded curried chicken or pulled pork, aoili, sliders etc.

The first are what you order for the table, it is typical to order 2 or more for a table of 4+ and you pick and choose what you want to snack on while having your drink. The second, the pintxos, are more everyday snacks that you get at the bar when you order a drink. You might have like 3 pintxos for light lunch or dinner and you choose from a variety of them.

I would recommend trying the croquettas, they're one of the best kinds of Spanish food IMO, it's a super simple way to reuse leftover meat or cheese. You have to kind of deep fry them in olive oil and the bechamel-type sauce they're made from must be frozen or very cold when you cook them.

last_replies.com:
I never thought I would growing up poor, but I now go through maybe a dozen 30g tins a month of caviar with entertaining and clients etc.

There is definitely a gulf between cheaper roe and sturgeon caviar, and then basic caviar and fine caviar. You can get examples from Iran, China, Bulgaria, Russia and the US now, and a few other nations are making it but are in early production stages so you won't see a huge amount outside of specialist suppliers.

You probably won't notice the difference between entry and high-end sturgeon unless you eat a lot of caviar, but thats the same for pretty much all luxury items.

You should splash out and get an entry level sturgeon caviar instead of a roe if you are treating yourself. The world is going to hell so why not treat yourself, but don't feel the next to flex for premium grade if it's just a present to yourself.

Also lumpfish isn't the same as sturgeon caviar, some people try to pass it off as an inferior product and it's really not anywhere near as good.

For extras either blini or thin rice crackers with sour cream/creme freche, then some finely diced shallots, fresh dill and maybe some hard boiled egg yolks which you can dice and dust over the top.

They're not like oysters so you should actually try and keep the flavour instead of covering it with hot sauce or mignonette, so my advice would be to have it as plain as possible to start and work up from there.

Also pair it with a dry white wine (pouilly-fuse, montrachet etc) or a very dry sherry (manzanilla is always a good starting point). Champagne is always good but I get a bit of acid which can counteract the delicate flavour.

Anyway, enjoy the caviar and appreciate the finer things in life fren
